The paper deals with the representation, approximation, and learning of submodular functions, which are commonly studied in the fields of discrete mathematics, optimization, and machine learning. The use of decision trees and spectral norms suggests a connection to machine learning and data analysis, placing it in the categories of cs.LG and cs.AI. The focus on submodular functions and their properties, as well as the use of information theory and computational complexity, suggests a connection to discrete mathematics and theoretical computer science, placing it in the categories of cs.DS, cs.IT, and cs.CC.
